## 10. **Important Compounds and Uses**

| Compound              | Type                     | Use                         |
| --------------------- | ------------------------ | --------------------------- |
| NaCl (table salt)     | Alkali halide            | Food, industry              |
| NaOH (caustic soda)   | Alkali hydroxide         | Soap, paper industry        |
| Ca(OH)₂ (slaked lime) | Alkaline earth hydroxide | Soil neutralizer            |
| CaCO₃ (limestone)     | Alkaline earth carbonate | Cement, chalk               |
| MgSO₄ (Epsom salt)    | Sulfate                  | Medicine, bath salt         |
| BaSO₄                 | Sulfate                  | X-ray imaging (barium meal) |

---

## 11. **Biological Importance**

* **Na⁺ and K⁺**: Nerve impulse conduction, osmotic balance.
* **Ca²⁺**: Bone and teeth formation, blood clotting.
* **Mg²⁺**: Present in chlorophyll, enzyme activation.

---

## 12. **Summary of Group Trends**

| Property                    | Alkali Metals            | Alkaline Earth Metals    |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------ | ------------------------ |
| Reactivity                  | Very high                | High (less than alkalis) |
| Ionization Energy           | Low                      | Higher than alkalis      |
| Flame Test                  | Characteristic colors    | Characteristic colors    |
| Basic Strength of Hydroxide | Very strong              | Moderate to strong       |
| Solubility of Hydroxides    | Increases down the group | Increases down the group |
| Solubility of Sulfates      | Mostly soluble           | Decreases down the group |

---

## 13. **Conclusion**

Alkali and alkaline earth metals are chemically reactive, particularly with water, oxygen, and halogens. Their compounds are essential in daily life and industry, ranging from food and construction to medicine and energy. Understanding their periodic trends and reactivity helps in predicting their behavior and applications in various chemical contexts.

